/**
 * @mainpage MLE Game Engine
 *
 * This is just a test doc generated by chatgpt. DO NOT TAKE THIS AS A REAL THING.
 *
 * Welcome to the documentation for the **MLE Game Engine** — a modular, high-performance engine
 * written in modern C++23 with Lua scripting and Vulkan rendering.
 *
 * ---
 *
 * ## ✨ Features
 *
 * - **Modern C++23 Core** — built with safety and clarity in mind.
 * - **Lua Scripting** — supports runtime behavior customization and full user modding.
 * - **Vulkan Backend** — low-level graphics API for maximum rendering performance.
 * - **GLFW** — cross-platform window and input handling.
 * - **GLM** — for vector/matrix math aligned with GLSL.
 * - **spdlog** — fast, extensible logging with formatted output.
 * - **No exceptions** — the engine is compiled with `-fno-exceptions` and avoids `throw`.
 * - **Expected-based initialization** — constructors are private; all construction goes through `static Expected<T> create()`.
 *
 * ---
 *
 * ## 📁 Project Structure
 *
 * - `docs/` — Doxygen documentation files.
 * - `external/` — Third-party libraries.
 * - `res/` — Engine internal resources (logo, Lua core scripts, default font, etc.).
 * - `scripts/` — Development and environment helper scripts.
 * - `src/` — Engine source code.
 * - `tests/` — Automated test files.
 * - `tools/` — Internal engine tools (e.g., asset processors, inspectors).
 *
 * ---
 *
 * ## 🧠 Core Design Principles
 *
 * - **Modular**: Each subsystem (UI, rendering, scripting) is self-contained.
 * - **Explicit Error Handling**: Initialization uses `Expected<T>` instead of exceptions.
 * - **Minimal Boilerplate**: Users define a `config()` function and include `Entry.inl`.
 * - **Clean Logging and Assertions**: Unified macros like `MLE_ASSERT`, `MLE_UNREACHABLE_LOG`.
 *
 * ---
 *
 * ## 🚀 Getting Started
 *
 * To create a game or app using MLE:
 *
 * 1. Define your configuration function:
 *    @code{.cpp}
 *    mle::core::CI config() {
 *        mle::core::CI ci;
 *        ci.name = "My Game";
 *        ci.width = 1280;
 *        ci.height = 720;
 *        return ci;
 *    }
 *    @endcode
 *
 * 2. Include the engine entry point:
 *    @code{.cpp}
 *    #include "Entry.inl"
 *    @endcode
 *
 * This sets up the engine, initializes runtime systems, and starts the main loop.
 *
 * ---
 *
 * ## 🧭 Coding Conventions
 *
 * - **No Exceptions**: The engine is compiled with `-fno-exceptions`. All error handling uses return codes or `Expected<T>`.
 * - **No shared ownership**: `shared_ptr` is a code smell. All ownership is explicit.
 *
 * ### Ownership Types
 * - `<T>Hnd` → owning handle (`std::unique_ptr<T>`)
 * - `<T>Ref` → non-owning, nullable or re-assignable reference (`T*`-like)
 *   - Caller must guarantee that the referenced object outlives the receiver.
 *
 * Example:
 * @code{.cpp}
 * using MeshHnd = std::unique_ptr<Mesh>;
 * using MeshRef = TRef<Mesh>;
 * @endcode
 *
 * ### Object Lifecycle
 * - All engine types have private constructors.
 * - Use `static Expected<T> create(...)` to initialize engine objects safely.
 *
 * ### Casting
 * - **This is personal**. Cpp style casts are ugly. I wish I could use (x as T) but I cant, so...
 * - Use `as<T>(x)` instead of `static_cast<T>(x)`.
 * - Use `asPtr<T>(x)` instead of `reinterpret_cast<T>(x)` for ptr to ptr.
 * - Use `asSelf<T>(x)` instead of `reinterpret_cast<T>(x)` for casting UserPtr to self reference.
 * - Use reinterpret_cast for anything else.
 * - No dynamic cast. We use -fno-rtti
 *
 * ---
 *
 * ## 🔍 Assertions and Error Handling
 *
 * This engine uses custom macros to enforce invariants:
 *
 * - `MLE_ASSERT(cond)` — basic assertion with a default message.
 * - `MLE_ASSERT_LOG(cond, ...)` — assert with custom message.
 * - `MLE_UNREACHABLE` — marks logically unreachable code.
 * - `MLE_UNREACHABLE_TODO` — marks code paths left as TODOs.
 *
 * All of these are active in debug mode, and optimize away in release.
 *
